But it is still sorting alphabetically. Do I need special options or widgets to sort Ajax data? No matter what I do with the table, it is always sorting alphabetically.

Oh, they are different in both tables? In that case you can check the table id or class name in the formatter:

```js
group_formatter : function(txt, col, table, c, wo) {
  return table.id === 'table1' ? 'Departures from ' + txt : txt;
}
```

Hi @Herst!

Hmm, it appears the issue is actually a css3StickyHeaders widget option.

Set the [`cssStickyHeaders_filteredToTop`](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-widget-sticky-header.html#stickyheaders-filteredtotop)<sup>&dagger;</sup> to `false` and everything should be okay - [demo](http://jsfiddle.net/pcmsL943/32/)

```js
$('#table1').tablesorter({
    //delayInit: true,
    // debug: true,
    theme: 'blue',
    widgets: ['zebra', 'filter', 'math', 'cssStickyHeaders'],
    widgetOptions: {
        filter_liveSearch: false,
        cssStickyHeaders_filteredToTop: false
    }
});
```

&dagger; *Note*: The link to that option points to the sticky headers widget demo and not the css sticky headers widget demo because the options are all the same, the only difference is the `css` in front.... and I'm too lazy to duplicate the options section in the other demo. :grin:

Hi @airthomas!

I saw the demo a few days ago, and today it looks different and the left menu isn't opening... anyway, I think the easiest fix would be to also add the "open" class to the content element, and use something like this ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/abkNM/9110/) not working):

```css
.FW_LeftMenu.close,
.FW_Content.close .tablesorter-sticky-wrapper {
  margin-left: -150px;
}
```

> conn.send("/queue/test", "test", headers={"test": r'\c\n'})
> ends up sending test:\c\n on the wire which is incorrect; both backslashes should be doubled.

That's not what I see in unit testing.  I see this output...

```
pass 1 {'test': '\\c\\n'}
pass 2 {'test': '\\c\\n'}
pass 3 {'test': '\\c\\n'}
```

So, at least to me, it seems to be working, and seems idempotent... (admittedly I haven't checked the actual send itself).

Agreed that send_frame should probably be explicitly private though...

