Hi @jcalebgood and @Renesco,

this behavior is due to the tabulation of the log and sigmoid functions in [src/model.cc](https://github.com/facebookresearch/fastText/blob/master/src/model.cc#L301). It can be avoided by replacing these two functions by
```c++
real Model::log(real x) const {
  if (x > 1.0) {
    return 0.0;
  }                                                                                                                                                                
  return std::log(x + 1e-6);
}

real Model::sigmoid(real x) const {
  if (x < -MAX_SIGMOID) {
    return 0.0;
  } else if (x > MAX_SIGMOID) {
    return 1.0;
  } else {                                                                                                                                                         
    return 1.0 / (1.0 + std::exp(-x));
  }
}
```

@lobocv 
pytest is a wonderful unit test framework.  If you haven't already checked it out our [Contributor's Guide](https://github.com/python-cmd2/cmd2/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) has some good suggestions for using it.  In particular, I would highly recommend the **xdist** plugin for running tests in parallel - it really speeds things up.

Honestly, the vast majority of our tests are integration tests, not unit tests.  So please don't take what we have as an example of how to write good unit tests though ;-)

@salamanders SMOTE (oversampling) is usually my "go to" approach, followed by One-Sided-Selection (undersampling). In my experience, it depends on the amount of data and imbalance ratio you have.

But keep in mind that it depends, there is no "killer" approach. I once used SMOTE and One Sided Selection in a large dataset (~100K samples/ 4K features), which ended up achieving the same results as RandomOverSampling of the minority class and RandomUnderSampling of the majority. When you're dealing with large datasets, time is also an important aspect.

Best of luck,

@RignonNoel I'm not aware of anyone working on this yet. A PR would be very welcome.

The ADDING_ESPS.md file is a good starting point. I put that together pretty quickly, so let me know if you have any questions. And a work-in-progress PR can be a good place to discuss specific code, whenever you're ready.

I'd recommend creating an Anymail Requests backend that calls SendInBlue's REST API directly (rather than trying to use their Python client library). Their API uses straightforward JSON payloads and responses, so some good examples to start from are the [Postmark backend](https://github.com/anymail/django-anymail/blob/master/anymail/backends/postmark.py) and the *unreleased* [Mailjet *v3.1* backend](https://github.com/anymail/django-anymail/blob/feature_mailjet_v3.1/anymail/backends/mailjet.py) (on the feature_mailjet_v3.1 branch).

